{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24 
{\cf1\f1\fs22 36}In the fourteenth year of the reign of Hezekiah, Sennacherib, King of Assyria, after having assaulted and captured all the fortified cities of Judah,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}despatched his Chief Officer from Lachish with a large force against King Hezekiah in Jerusalem. Near the conduit of the upper pool, where he had taken up his position on the Fuller\uc1\u8217*s Field Road,{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}he was visited by a deputation consisting of Eliakim the son of Hilkiah, Governor of the Palace, Shebna the Secretary, and Joah the son of Asaph, the Recorder.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}The Chief Officer began: \uc1\u8220*This is the message from the Great King, the King of Assyria: I desire{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}you to deliver it to Hezekiah. \uc1\u8217*What sort of confidence is this that you cherish? Do you imagine that in war a mere word of the lips is the equivalent of wisdom and strength? Now who is it you are{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}trusting in, that you presume to rebel against me? Of course you are trusting to Egypt, that staff of broken reed, which will enter and piece the hand of the man who leans upon it: that is all that Pharaoh King of Egypt will prove to those who{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}trust to him. If, however, you tell me you are trusting to your God the {\scaps Lord}, why, that is the very god whose sanctuaries and altars Hezekiah has abolished, commanding the people of Judah and Jerusalem to confine their worship to the altar at this{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}place? Now, make a wager, if you like, with my lord the King of Assyria: I am prepared to furnish you with two thousand horses, if you on your part{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}can supply them with riders. (But if you cannot), how do you propose to repel the onset of one of the least of my lord\uc1\u8217*s officers? Yet you trust to Egypt{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}for chariots and horsemen. And now do you imagine that I have not the {\scaps Lord}\uc1\u8217*s sanction for invading this land with a view to its destruction? Why, it is the {\scaps Lord} himself who commissioned me to invade this land and destroy it.\uc1\u8217*\uc1\u8221*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Thereupon Eliakim, Shebna, and Joah asked the Chief Officer to be good enough not to speak to them in Hebrew, in the hearing of the people on the wall, but in Aramaic, which they assured him{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}they understood. \uc1\u8220*No,\uc1\u8221* replied the Officer, \uc1\u8220*it is not to your lord and yourself that my lord has sent me with this message, but precisely to the men on the wall, whom your policy is likely to reduce to eating their own filth and drinking their own water. \uc1\u8221*
